{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "While our paper argues that many of the observed issues of current language models can be attributed to violation of one or more of the maxims, we emphasize that we do not claim that every maxim must be satisfied in every conversation in order to be deemed a \"good\" conversation.",
    "Rather the proposed maxims serve as dimensions for analyzing human-AI conversations.",
    "Some maxims may be less important, or even not important at all, in some contexts (Kasirzadeh and Gabriel, 2023).",
    "Therefore, instead of studying a model's ability to satisfy the maxims, which would likely lead to relatively noisy and inconclusive results simply due to the sheer variability of contexts (Kovač et al., 2023), operationalization should instead focus on a model's ability to interpret the maxims.",
    "We argue that a model's ability to accurately interpret the maxims is a necessary precondition for satisfying them if the particular context demands it."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
